A055005.name: Number of nonnegative integer 3 X 3 matrices with no zero rows or columns and with sum of elements equal to n.

Formulas for general bases b > 1 (b = 10 for this sequence).
a(n) = n + (b+1)*sum_{k>0} (-1)^k*floor(n/b^k). Both sums are finite with floor(log_b(n)) as the highest index.
a(n) = a(n mod b^k) + (-1)^k*a(floor(n/b^k)), for all k>=0.
a(n) = (-1)^k*A225693(A004086(n)), where k = is the number of trailing 0's of n, formally, k = max(j | n == 0 mod 10^j).
a(A004086(A004086(n))) = (-1)^k*a(n), where k = is the number of trailing 0's in the decimal representation of n. (End)

formula: The n-th power of this array has a generating function E(x*y)/E(y)^n. In particular, the matrix inverse A008459 has a generating function E(y)*E(x*y).
Recurrence equation for the row polynomials: R(n,x) = x^n - Sum_{k = 0..n-1} binomial(n,k)^2*R(k,x) with initial value R(0,x) = 1.

There appears to be a connection between the zeros of the Bessel function E(x) and the real zeros of the row polynomials R(n,x). Let alpha denote the root of E(x) = 0 that is smallest in absolute magnitude. Numerically, alpha = -1.44579 64907 ... ( = -(A115365/2)^2). It appears that the real zeros of R(n,x) approach zeros of E(alpha*x) as n increases. A numerical example is given below. Indeed, it may be the case that lim_{n -> inf} R(n,x)/R(n,0) = E(alpha*x) for arbitrary complex x. (End)

A055137.name: Regard triangle of rencontres numbers (see A008290) as infinite matrix, compute inverse, read by rows.
formula: k-th column has o.g.f. x^k(1-(k+2)x)/(1-x)^(k+2). k-th row gives coefficients of (x-k)(x+1)^k. - _Paul Barry_, Jan 25 2004
T(n,k) = Coefficientslist[Det[Table[If[i == j, x, 1], {i, 1, n}, {k, 1, n}],x]. - _Roger L. Bagula_, Feb 20 2009

Given a permutation p belonging to the symmetric group S_n, let fix(p) be the number of fixed points of p and sign(p) its parity. The row polynomials R(n,x) have a combinatorial interpretation as R(n,x) = (-1)^n*Sum_{permutations p in S_n} sign(p)*(-x)^(fix(p)). An example is given below.

Note: The polynomials P(n,x) = Sum_{permutations p in S_n} x^(fix(p)) are the row polynomials of the rencontres numbers A008290. The integral results Integral_{x = 0..n} R(n,x) dx = n/(n+1) = Integral_{x = 0..-1} R(n,x) dx lead to the identities Sum_{p in S_n} sign(p)*(-n)^(1 + fix(p))/(1 + fix(p)) = (-1)^(n+1)*n/(n+1) = Sum_{p in S_n} sign(p)/(1 + fix(p)). The latter equality was Problem B6 in the 66th William Lowell Putnam Mathematical Competition 2005. (End)

The e.g.f. in Copeland's 2008 comment implies this entry is an Appell sequence of polynomials P(n,x) with lowering and raising operators L = d/dx and R = x + d/dL log[exp(L)(1-L)] = x+1 - 1/(1-L) = x - L - L^2 - ... such that L P(n,x) = n P(n-1,x) and R P(n,x) = P(n+1,x).
The formalism of A133314 applies to the pair of entries A008290 and A055137.
The polynomials of this pair P_n(x) and Q_n(x) are umbral compositional inverses; i.e., P_n(Q.(x)) = x^n = Q_n(P.(x)), where, e.g., (Q.(x))^n = Q_n(x).

The exponential infinitesimal generator (infinigen) of this entry is the negated infinigen of A008290, the matrix (M) noted by Bala, related to A238363. Then e^M = [the lower triangular A008290], and e^(-M) = [the lower triangular A055137]. For more on the infinigens, see A238385. (End)

From the row g.f.s corresponding to Bagula's matrix example below, the n-th row polynomial has a zero of multiplicity n-1 at x = 1 and a zero at x = -n+1. Since this is an Appell sequence dP_n(x)/dx = n P_{n-1}(x), the critical points of P_n(x) have the same abscissas as the zeros of P_{n-1}(x); therefore, x = 1 is an inflection point for the polynomials of degree > 2 with P_n(1) = 0, and the one local extremum of P_n has the abscissa x = -n + 2 with the value (-n+1)^{n-1}, signed values of A000312. - _Tom Copeland_, Nov 15 2019

A055140.name: Triangle: matchings of 2n people with partners (of either sex) such that exactly k couples are left together.
formula: E.g.f.: e^(xt) e^(-t) (1-2t)^(-1/2) = e^(p.(x)*t)(from my 2008 comment).

L = D = d/dx and R = x + d[log[e^(L)(1-2L)^(-1/2)]]/dL = x - 1  + 1/(1-2D) = x + 2D + (2D)^2 + (2D)^3 + ... are the lowering and raising operators, i.e., L p_n(x) = n * p_(n-1)(x) and R p_n(x) = p_(n+1)(x); e.g., L p_2(x) = D (2 + x^2) = 2 x = 2 p_1(x) and R P_2(x) = (x + 2D + 4D^2 + ...) (2 + x^2) = 2x + x^3 + 4x + 8 = 8 + 6x + x^3 = p_3(x).
Umbral binomial convolution gives p_n(x) = (a. + x)^n = sum_{k = 0,..,n} C(n,k) a_(n-k) * x^k with (a.)^k = a_k = A053871(k).
The Appell sequence of umbral compositional inverses has the e.g.f. e^(xt) e^t (1-2t)^(1/2) associated with A055142. Cf. A231846 for a definition of umbral compositional inversion.
See A132382 and A133314 for more relations.

The row polynomials R(n,x) = sum{k = 0..n} T(n,k)x^k begin R(0,x) = 1, R(1,x) = 1, R(2,x) = 1 + x, R(3,x) = 1 + 3*x. They are related to the Narayana polynomials N(n,x) := sum {k = 1..n} 1/n*C(n,k)*C(n,k-1)*x^k through x*(1 + x)^n*R(n, x/(1 + x)^2) = N(n+1,x). For example, for n = 3, x*(1 + x)^3*(1 + 3*x/(1 + x)^2) = x + 6*x^2 + 6*x^3 + x^4, the 4th Narayana polynomial.
G.f.: M(x,y) satisfies: M(x,y)= 1 + x M(x,y) + y*x^2*M(x,y)^2. - _Geoffrey Critzer_, Feb 05 2014

Sum_{k=1..floor(n/2)} k * T(n,k) = A014531(n-1) for n>1. - _Alois P. Heinz_, Mar 29 2020

formula: Multiplicative with a(p^e) = (p^(e/2)*(p+1)-2)/(p-1) for even e and a(p^e) = 2*(p^((e+1)/2)-1)/(p-1) for odd e. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Nov 01 2001

a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} gcd(gcd(n,k),n/gcd(n,k))/phi(n/gcd(n,k)), where phi = A000010. - _Richard L. Ollerton_, May 09 2021

A055196.name: Numbers n such that n | sigma(n)*phi(n) and n is primitive.

A055201.name: Numbers k such that A005728(k) is prime.

A055202.name: Smallest integer that can be expressed as p+2m^2 in more ways than any smaller number, where m >= 0 and p = 1 or prime.

A055203.name: Number of different relations between n intervals on a line.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{i=2..2n} lambda(i, n), with lambda(p, 1) = 1 if p = 2, otherwise 0; lambda(p, n) = (p*(p-1)/2)*(lambda(p, n-1) + 2*lambda(p-1, n-1) + lambda(p-2, n-1)).
Row sums of A122193. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Aug 24 2006

A055204.name: Squarefree part of n!: n! divided by its largest square divisor.
formula: log a(n) ~ n log 2. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Apr 03 2012
sqrt(n!) = A055772(n) * sqrt(a(n)). - _Alonso del Arte_, Feb 16 2015

formula: a(n) = A000005(n^2)-A000005(n) because the number of square divisors of n^2 equals the number of divisors of n.

A055207.name: Sum of n-th powers of digits of n.

A055208.name: Table T(n,k) = sum of k-th powers of digits of n read by antidiagonals (n >= 1, k >= 1).

A055209.name: a(n) = Product_{i=0..n} i!^2.
formula: a(n) = Product_{i=0..n} i^(2*n - 2*i + 2). - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Jan 12 2012

A055210.name: Sum of totients of square divisors of n.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{d is square and divides n} phi(d).
Multiplicative with a(p^e) = (p^(e+1)+1)/(p+1) for even e and a(p^e) = (p^e+1)/(p+1) for odd e. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Dec 01 2001
Conjecture: a(n) = sigma_2(n/core(n))/sigma_1(n/core(n)) = A001157(A008833(n))/A000203(A008833(n)) for all n > 0. - _Velin Yanev_, Oct 13 2019

A055211.name: Lesser Fortunate numbers.
formula: a(n) = 1 + the difference between the n-th Primorial less one and the previous prime.

A055212.name: Number of composite divisors of n.
formula: a(n) = tau(n)-omega(n)-1, where tau=A000005 and omega=A001221. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jun 13 2003
G.f.: -x/(1 - x) + Sum_{k>=1} (x^k - x^prime(k))/((1 - x^k)*(1 - x^prime(k))). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Mar 21 2017

A055213.name: Number of n-piece positions at checkers, for n=1 ... 24.

A055214.name: a(0) = 1; a(n) = 2*n*a(n-1) - 1 for n >= 1.
formula: a(n) = ceiling(2^n * n! * (2-sqrt(e))) = ceiling(A000165(n) * (2-sqrt(e))). - _Gary Detlefs_, Jul 18 2010

A055215.name: A path-counting array, read by rows: T(i,j)=number of paths from (0,0) to (i-j,j) using steps (1 unit right and 1 unit up) or (1 unit right and 2 units up).

a(n) = 3^n * 3/2 + O(3^n/sqrt(n)). - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Dec 02 2015

A055222.name: T(2n+6,n), array T as in A055216.

formula: G.f.: Sum_{n>=1} -log(1 - n*x^n)/n = Sum_{n>=0} a(n) x^n/n. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Aug 04 2002

A055229.name: Greatest common divisor of largest square dividing n and squarefree part of n.
formula: Multiplicative with a(p^e)=1 for even e, a(p)=1, a(p^e)=p for odd e>1. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Apr 30 2002
a(n) = core(n)*rad(n/core(n))/rad(n), where core = A007913 and rad = A007947. - Conjecture by _Velin Yanev_, proof by _David J. Seal_, Sep 19 2017

A055230.name: Greatest common divisor of largest square dividing n! and squarefree part of n!.

A055231.name: Powerfree part of n: product of primes that divide n only once.
formula: Multiplicative with a(p) = p and a(p^e) = 1 for e > 1. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Nov 01 2001
Dirichlet g.f.: zeta(s)*Product_{primes p} (1 + p^(1-s) - p^(-s) - p^(1-2s) + p^(-2s)). - _R. J. Mathar_, Dec 21 2011
a(n) = A007947(n)/A071773(n). - observed by _Velin Yanev_, Aug 27 2017, confirmed by _Antti Karttunen_, Nov 28 2017

a(n*m) = a(n)*a(m)/(gcd(n,a(m))*gcd(m,a(n))) for all n and m > 0 (conjectured). - _Velin Yanev_, Feb 06 2019. [This follows easily from the comment of _Vladeta Jovovic_. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Mar 14 2019]
Dirichlet g.f.: zeta(s-1) * zeta(s) * Product_{primes p} (1 - p^(1-3*s) + p^(2-3*s) - p^(2-2*s) + p^(-2*s) - p^(-s)).

formula: a(n) = ((n+1)^3 + ceiling((n+1)/2)^2 + floor((n+1)/2)^2)/2. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Apr 15 2016

Regarded as a triangle, T(n, k) = 3^n + 3^k, because 3^n + 3^n < 3^(n+1) + 3^0 for all n > 0.

A055236.name: Sums of two powers of 4.

A055243.name: First differences of A001628 (Fibonacci convolution).
formula: a(n)= ((5*n^2+37*n+50)*F(n+1)+4*(n+1)*F(n))/50 with F(n)=A000045(n) (Fibonacci numbers) (from Turban reference eq. (2.17)).
Comments from _Peter Bala_, Oct 25 2007 (Start): Since F(-n) = (-1)^(n+1)*F(n), we can use the previous formula to extend the sequence to negative values of n; we find a(-n) = (-1)^n* A129707(n-3).

a(n-3) = sum {k = 2..floor((n+1)/2)} C(k,2)C(n-k,k-1) = (1/2)*G''(n,1), where the polynomial G(n,x) := sum {k = 1..floor((n+1)/2)} C(n-k,k-1)* x^k = x^((n+1)/2) * F(n, 1/sqrt(x)) and where F(n,x) denotes the n-th Fibonacci polynomial. Since G(n,1) yields the Fibonacci numbers A000045 and G'(n,1) yields the second-order Fibonacci numbers A010049, a(n) may be considered as the sequence of third-order Fibonacci numbers.

For n >= 4, the polynomials sum {k = 0..n} C(n,k)* G''(n-k,1)*(-x)^k appear to satisfy a Riemann hypothesis; their zeros appear to lie on the vertical line Re x = 1/2 in the complex plane. Compare with the remarks in A094440 and A010049. (End)

A055244.name: Number of certain stackings of n+1 squares on a double staircase.
formula: G.f.: (1-x+x^3)/(1-x-x^2)^2 (from Turban reference eq.(3.3) with t=1).
a(n)=((n+5)*F(n+1)+(2*n-3)*F(n))/5 with F(n)=A000045(n) (Fibonacci numbers) (from Turban reference eq.(3.9)).
a(n) = A001629(n+1) + F(n-1). - _Gary W. Adamson_, Jul 27 2007

A055245.name: Numerator sequence of mean length of certain stackings of n+1 squares on a double staircase.
formula: a(n) = ((5*n^2+3*n-27)*F(n)+(19*n+25)*F(n+1))/25 with F(n)=A000045(n) (Fibonacci numbers) (from Turban reference eq.(3.12)).

A055246.name: At step number k >= 1 the 2^(k-1) open intervals that are erased from [0,1] in the Cantor middle-third set construction are I(k,n) = (a(n)/3^k, (1+a(n))/3^k), n=1..2^(k-1).
formula: a(n+1) = A074938(n) + A074939(n); A074938: odd numbers in A005836, A074939: even numbers in A005836. - _Philippe Deléham_, Jul 10 2005

A055247.name: Related to A055246 and A005836. Used for boundaries of open intervals which have to be erased in the Cantor middle third set construction.
formula: a(1) = 1, a(n) = 3^ceiling( log_2( n ) ) - a( 2^ceiling( log_2( n ) ) + 1 - n ). - Juan Jose Alba Gonzalez (jjalba(AT)gmail.com), May 16 2006

A055248.name: Triangle of partial row sums of triangle A007318(n,m) (Pascal's triangle). Triangle A008949 read backwards. Riordan (1/(1-2x), x/(1-x)).
formula: a(n, m) = Sum_{k=m..n} A007318(n, k) (partial row sums in columns m).
Column m recursion: a(n, m) = Sum_{j=m..n-1} a(j, m) + A007318(n, m) if n >= m >= 0, a(n, m) := 0 if n<m.
a(n, m) = Sum_{j=0..n} binomial(n, m+j). - _Paul Barry_, Feb 03 2005
Inverse binomial transform (by columns) of A112626. - _Ross La Haye_, Dec 31 2006

Exp(x) * e.g.f. for row n = e.g.f. for diagonal n. For example, for n = 3 we have exp(x)*(8 + 7*x + 4*x^2/2! + x^3/3!) = 8 + 15*x + 26*x^2/2! + 42*x^3/3! + 64*x^4/4! + .... The same property holds more generally for Riordan arrays of the form ( f(x), x/(1 - x) ).
Let M denote the present triangle. For k = 0,1,2,... define M(k) to be the lower unit triangular block array

\ 0  M/ having the k X k identity matrix I_k as the upper left block; in particular, M(0) = M. The infinite product M(0)*M(1)*M(2)*..., which is clearly well-defined, is equal to A143494 (but with a different offset). See the Example section. Cf. A106516. (End)
a(n,m) = Sum_{p=m..n} 2^(n-p)*binomial(p-1,m-1), n >= m >= 0, else 0. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Jan 09 2015
T(n, k) = 2^n - (1/2)*binomial(n, k-1)*hypergeom([1, n+1], [n-k+2], 1/2). - _Peter Luschny_, Oct 10 2019

A055249.name: Triangle of partial row sums (prs) of triangle A055248 (prs of Pascal's triangle A007318).
formula: a(n, m) = Sum_{k=m,..,n} ( A055248(n, k) ), n >= m >= 0, a(n, m) := 0 if n<m, (sequence of partial row sums in column m).
Column m recursion: a(n, m) = Sum_{j=m,..,(n-1)} ( a(j, m) ) + A055248(n, m), n >= m >= 0, a(n, m) := 0 if n<m.
a(n, m) = binomial(n, m) * 2F1(2, m-n; m+1; -1) where 2F1 is the hypergeometric function. _Jean-François Alcover_, Mar 11 2014

A055250.name: Seventh column of triangle A055249.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n+5} Sum_{i=0..n+5} (i-k) * C(n-k+5,i+3). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Sep 19 2017

A055251.name: Eighth column of triangle A055249.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n+6} Sum_{i=0..n+6} (i-k) * C(n-k+6,i+4). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Sep 19 2017

A055252.name: Triangle of partial row sums (prs) of triangle A055249.

Regarded as a triangle T(n, k) = 7^n + 7^k, so as a sequence a(n) = 7^A002262(n) + 7^A003056(n).

A055259.name: Sums of two powers of 8.
formula: a(n) = 8^(n-trinv(n))+8^trinv(n), where trinv(n) = floor((1+sqrt(1+8*n))/2) = A002262(n) and n-trinv(n) = A003056(n)
Regarded as a triangle T(n, k) = 8^n + 8^k, so as a sequence a(n) = 8^A002262(n) + 8^A003056(n).

A055376.name: CIK transform of Pascal's triangle A007318.
formula: Let b(n,k) be the number in row n and column k. We have b(0,0) = 0 and b(n,k) = (1/n)*Sum_{d|gcd(n,k)} phi(d)*C(n/d, k/d)*(2^{n/d}-1) for n>=1 and k>=0. Here, C(n,k) = binomial(n,k).
G.f. for row n>=1: Sum_{k>=0} b(n,k)*y^k = (1/n)*Sum_{d|n} phi(d)*(2^{n/d}-1)*(1+y^d)^{n/d}.
G.f. for column k = 0: Sum_{n>=1} b(n,k=0)*x^n = Sum_{s>=1} (phi(s)/s)*log((1-x^s)/(1-2*x^s)) = -x/(1-x) - Sum_{s>=1} (phi(s)/s)*log(1-2*x^s).
G.f. for column k >= 1: Sum_{n>=1} b(n,k)*x^n = Sum_{d|k} (phi(d)/d)*(g_{k/d}(2*x^d) - g_{k/d}(x^d)), where g_k(x) = Sum_{s=0..k-1} C(k-1, s)*(-1)^s/((k-s)*(1-x)^{k-s}).

A055455.name: T(n,n-5), array T as in A055450.

A055456.name: a(n) = smallest number which is not the sum of exactly 1 or of n earlier terms.
formula: If n-1>0 has not already appeared in sequence then a(n)=n-1, otherwise a(n)=n^2-n+1

A055457.name: 5^a(n) exactly divides 5n. Or, 5-adic valuation of 5n.
formula: Multiplicative with a(p^e) = e+1 if p = 5, 1 otherwise.
Dirichlet g.f.: zeta(s)/(1-1/5^s). - _R. J. Mathar_, Feb 09 2011
a(5n) = 1 + a(n).  a(5n+k) = 1 for k = 1..4. - _Robert Israel_, Dec 07 2015
G.f. satisfies A(x^5) = A(x) - x/(1-x). - _Robert Israel_, Dec 08 2015

A055458.name: a(n) = smallest composite solution x to the equation phi(x+2n) = phi(x)+2n.

A055459.name: a(n) = number of permutations of {1,...,n} which are twice but not 3-times reformable.

A055460.name: Number of primes with odd exponents in the prime power factorization of n!.

A055461.name: Square decrescendo subsequences: triangle T(n,k) = (n-k)^2, n >= 1, 0 <= k < n.
formula: G.f. as triangle: x*(1+x)/((1-x*y)*(1-x)^3). - _Robert Israel_, Jan 18 2018

A055462.name: Superduperfactorials: product of first n superfactorials.
formula: a(n) = a(n-1)*A000178(n) = Product[(i!)^(n-i+1)] over 1 <= i <= n = Product[i^((n-i+1)(n-i+2)/2)] over 1 <= i <= n.
log a(n) = (1/6) n^3 log n - (11/36) n^3 + O(n^2 log n). - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Jan 13 2012

a(n) = exp((6 + 13 n + 9 n^2 + 2 n^3 - 8*(n + 2)*log(A)-2*(n + 2)^2*log(2*Pi) + 4*(2 n + 1)*logG(n + 2) - 4*(n + 1)^2*logGamma(n + 2) + 8*psi(-3, n + 2))/8) where A is the Glaisher-Kinkelin constant, logG(z) is the logarithm of the Barnes G function (A000178), and psi(-3, z) is a polygamma function of negative order (i.e., the second iterated integral of logGamma(z)). - _Jan Mangaldan_, Mar 21 2013

A055464.name: Numbers n such that sum of EulerPhi and DivisorSum is an integer multiple of the number of divisors.
formula: Solutions to Phi[x]+Sigma[x] = kd[x] or A000203(n)+A000010(n) = k*A000005(n), where k is integer.

A055465.name: Composite numbers for which sum of EulerPhi and Divisor-Sum is an integer multiple of the number of divisors.
formula: Composite integer solutions of Phi[x]+Sigma[x] = kd[x] or A000203(n)+A000010(n) = k*A000005(n), where k is integer.

A055466.name: Numbers n such that d(n)^2 divides phi(n) + sigma(n).
formula: Integer solutions of Phi[x]+Sigma[x] = kd[x]^2 or A000203(n)+A000010(n) = k*A000005(n)^2, where k is integer.

A055467.name: Nonprime numbers for which phi(n) + sigma(n) is an integer multiple of the cube of the number of divisors.
formula: Integer solutions of phi(x) + sigma(x) = k*d(x)^3 or A000203(n) + A000010(n) = k*A000005(n)^3, where k is an integer.

A055468.name: Composite numbers for which Sum of EulerPhi and Divisor-Sum is an integer multiple of the 4th power of the number of divisors.
formula: Integer solutions of Phi[x]+Sigma[x] = kd[x]^4 or A000203(n)+A000010(n) = k*A000005(n)^4, where k is integer.

A055469.name: Primes of the form k(k+1)/2+1 (i.e., central polygonal numbers, or one more than triangular numbers).

A055470.name: Smallest number x > 1 such that phi(x) + sigma(x) = k*d(x)^n, i.e., the left-hand side is divisible by the n-th power of the number of divisors.
formula: Least integer x > 1 such that A000010(x) + A000203(x) = k*A000005(x)^n.

A055471.name: Divisible by the product of its nonzero digits.

A055472.name: Primes of the form k(k+1)/2+2 (i.e., two more than a triangular number).

A055473.name: Powers of ten written in base 2.

A055474.name: Powers of ten written in base 3.

A055475.name: Powers of ten written in base 4.

A055476.name: Powers of ten written in base 5.
formula: a(n) = A000866(n) followed by n zeros.

A055477.name: Powers of ten written in base 6.

A055478.name: Powers of ten written in base 7.

A055479.name: Powers of ten written in base 9.

A055481.name: Numbers k for which there exists some m such that k = Sum_{i=1..1+floor(log_10(k))} binomial(m, d_i), where d_i is the i-th digit of k.

A055482.name: There exists some k>0 such that n is the product of (k + digits of n).

A055483.name: a(n) = GCD of n and the reverse of n.

A055484.name: Number of unlabeled 3-element intersecting families (with not necessary distinct sets) of an n-element set.

A055485.name: Number of unlabeled 3-element intersecting families (with distinct sets) of an n-element set.

A055486.name: Number of solutions to sigma(x) = n!.

A055487.name: Least m such that phi(m) = n!.

A055488.name: Smallest number x such that sum of divisors of x is n!.
formula: a(n) = Min{x; Sigma[x] = n!} = Min{x; A000203(x) = A000142(n)}

A055489.name: Largest number x such that sum of divisors of x is n!.
formula: a(n) = Max{x; Sigma[x] = n!} = Max{x; A000203(x) = A000142(n)}

A055490.name: Factorial primes: primes of the form n! - 1.
formula: p = n!-1 for some n given in A002982.

A055491.name: Smallest square divisible by n divided by largest square which divides n.
formula: If n is written as Product(Pj^Ej) then a(n) = Product(Pj^(2*(Ej mod 2))).

A055492.name: Numbers n such that LCM{1, ..., n} is a minimal number.

A055493.name: Numbers n such that Sum_{k=1..n} k! - 2 is prime.

A055494.name: Numbers n such that n^2 - n + 1 is prime.

A055495.name: Numbers n such that there exists a pair of mutually orthogonal Latin squares of order n.

A055498.name: a(0)=0, a(1)=1, a(n) = smallest prime >= a(n-1) + a(n-2).
formula: a(n+1) = nextprime(a(n) + a(n-1)) where nextprime(n) is smallest prime >= n.
a(n) is asymptotic to c*phi^n where phi = (1 + sqrt(5))/2 and c = 1.086541275044988562375... - _Benoit Cloitre_, May 02 2004
a(n)=A055499(n-1) for n>3. - _Robert G. Wilson v_, Mar 13 2013
a(n) = A007918(a(n-1) + a(n-2)) for n > 1. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Nov 13 2014

A055499.name: a(0)=0, a(1)=1, a(n) = smallest prime > a(n-1)+a(n-2).

A055500.name: a(0)=1, a(1)=1, a(n) = largest prime <= a(n-1)+a(n-2).
formula: a(n) is asymptotic to C*phi^n where phi=(1+sqrt(5))/2 and C=0.25861637901860700965101922576495456677... - _Benoit Cloitre_, Apr 21 2003
a(n) = A007917(a(n-1) + a(n-2)) for n > 1. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, May 01 2013
a(n) >= prime(n-1) for n > 1, by Ishikawa's theorem. - _Jonathan Sondow_, Sep 21 2013

A055501.name: a(0)=1, a(1)=2, a(n) = largest prime < a(n-1)+a(n-2).

A055502.name: a(0)=0, a(1)=2, a(n) = smallest prime > a(n-1)+a(n-2).

A055503.name: Take n points in general position in the plane; draw all the (infinite) straight lines joining them; sequence gives number of connected regions formed.

A055506.name: Number of solutions to the equation phi(x) = n!.

A055507.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} d(k)*d(n+1-k), where d(k) is number of positive divisors of k.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{i >= 1, j >= 1} x^(i+j-1)/(1-x^i)/(1-x^j). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Nov 11 2001
Working with an offset of 2, it appears that the o.g.f is equal to the Lambert series sum {n >= 2} A072031(n-1)*x^n/(1 - x^n). - _Peter Bala_, Dec 09 2014

A055508.name: H is the first, fifth, sixteenth, ..., letter in the sequence not counting spaces and commas.

A055509.name: Number of odd primes in sequence obtained in 3x+1 (or Collatz) problem starting at n.
formula: If n is odd, a(n) = a(3*n+1) + A010051(n).
If n is even, a(n) = a(n/2). (End)

A055510.name: Largest odd prime in sequence obtained in 3x+1 (or Collatz) problem starting at n, or 0 if no such prime is found.

A055513.name: Class number h = h- * h+ of cyclotomic field Q( exp(2 Pi / prime(n)) ).

A055514.name: Composite numbers that are the sum of a string of consecutive prime numbers and are divisible by the first and last primes.

A055515.name: (2^n -1)/product(2^p -1) where the product is over all distinct primes p that divide n.
formula: For p prime, a(p) = 1. - _Michel Marcus_, May 18 2014
For p prime, a(p^2) = A051156(n). - _Michel Marcus_, May 18 2014

A055516.name: Largest integer k such that k | Phi(k) + d(k) + n.

A055517.name: Largest integer k such that k | Phi(k) - d(k) + n, or 0 if no such k exists, where d() is the number of divisors.

A055518.name: a_{k+1} = 6*a_k + 11*a_{k-1} - 19*a_{k-2} - 4*a_{k-3} + a_{k-4}, a_1=1, a_2=2, a_3=19, a_4=118, a_5=875.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} Fibonacci(k)^4*a(n-k), a(0)=1. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Apr 23 2003

A055519.name: a_{k+1} = 9*a_k + 33*a_{k-1} - 76*a_{k-2} - 33*a_{k-3} + 9*a_{k-4} + a_{k-5}, a_1=1, a_2=2, a_3=35, a_4=312, a_5=3779, a_6=41590.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} Fibonacci(k)^5*a(n-k), a(0)=1. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Apr 23 2003

A055520.name: Numbers n such that 30*R_n + 1 is prime, where R_n = 11...1 is the repunit (A002275) of length n.

A055522.name: Largest area of a Pythagorean triangle with n as length of one of the three sides (in fact as a leg).

A055523.name: Longest other leg of a Pythagorean triangle with n as length of a leg.

A055524.name: Longest other side of a Pythagorean triangle with n as length of one of the three sides (in fact n is a leg and a(n) the hypotenuse).

A055525.name: Shortest other side of a Pythagorean triangle having n as length of one of the three sides.

A055526.name: Shortest hypotenuse of a Pythagorean triangle with n as length of a leg.

A055527.name: Shortest other leg of a Pythagorean triangle with n as length of a leg.

A055529.name: Number of bits needed in mantissa to express n! exactly.

A055530.name: The recurrence b(k) = 10*b(k-1) + k^n with b(0)=0 has b(k)/10^k converging to a(n)/9^(n+1).

A055531.name: Number of labeled order relations on n nodes in which longest chain has 2 nodes.

A055532.name: Number of labeled order relations on n nodes in which longest chain has 3 nodes.

A055533.name: Number of labeled order relations on n nodes in which longest chain has n-1 nodes.
formula: D-finite with recurrence (n-2)^2*a(n) -n*(n-1)^2*a(n-1)=0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Mar 08 2021

A055534.name: Number of labeled order relations on n nodes in which longest chain has n-2 nodes.

A055535.name: Denominators in expansion of (1-x)^(-1/x)/e.
formula: Let a(n) be A055505, let b(n) be this sequence. Then (1+x)^(1/x) = exp(1)*a(n)/b(n) x^n.
a(n)/b(n) = Sum_{i>=n} s(i,i-n)/i! where s(n,m) is a Stirling number of the first kind.
exp(1) = 1 + Sum_{i>=1} s(i,i)/i! for the n = 1 case.

A055536.name: Number of asymmetric types of (3,n)-hypergraphs under action of symmetric group S_3.

A055537.name: Number of asymmetric types of (4,n)-hypergraphs under action of symmetric group S_4.

A055538.name: Number of asymmetric types of (3,n)-hypergraphs without isolated nodes, under action of symmetric group S_3; asymmetric n-covers of an unlabeled 3-set.

A055539.name: Number of asymmetric types of (4,n)-hypergraphs without isolated nodes, under action of symmetric group S_4; asymmetric n-covers of an unlabeled 4-set.

A055540.name: Total number of leaves (nodes of vertex degree 1) in all graphs of n nodes.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} k*A327371(n, k). - _Andrew Howroyd_, Sep 04 2019

A055541.name: Total number of leaves (nodes of vertex degree 1) in all labeled trees with n nodes.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} (A055314(n, k)*k). - _Christian G. Bower_, Jun 12 2000
E.g.f.: x*T(x) where T(x) is the e.g.f. for A000169. - _Geoffrey Critzer_, Feb 07 2012

A055542.name: Total number of nodes in all simple graphs of n nodes.

A055543.name: Total number of nodes in all trees with n nodes.
formula: O.g.f.: x d/dx A(x) where A(x) is the o.g.f. for A000055. - _Geoffrey Critzer_, Jul 06 2020

A055544.name: Total number of nodes in all rooted trees with n nodes.
formula: G.f.: x * (d/dx) x * Product_{k>=1} 1/(1 - x^k)^(a(k)/k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, May 26 2019

A055545.name: Number of matroids on n points.

A055547.name: Number of normal n X n matrices with entries {0,1}.
formula: a(n) >= 2^[n*(n+1)/2] = A006125(n+1) because all symmetric binary matrices (which have n*(n+1)/2 independent elements) are normal. - _R. J. Mathar_, Mar 22 2006

A055548.name: Number of normal n X n (-1,1)-matrices.

A055549.name: Number of normal n X n (-1,0,1)-matrices.

A055550.name: Number of Poulet numbers (or pseudoprimes to base 2, A001567) less than 10^n.

A055551.name: Number of base-2 Euler-Jacobi pseudoprimes (A047713) less than 10^n.

A055552.name: Number of base-2 strong pseudoprimes (A001262) less than 10^n.

A055553.name: Number of Carmichael numbers (A002997) less than 10^n.

A055554.name: An arithmetic progression each term of which is followed by at least 4 nonsquarefree consecutive integers.

A055556.name: Differences of arithmetic progressions of which the terms give chains of n consecutive nonsquarefree numbers if started with terms of A045882(n) or A051681(n).

A055557.name: Numbers n such that 3*R_n - 2 is prime, where R_n = 11...1 is the repunit (A002275) of length n.

A055561.name: Numbers n such that there are precisely 3 groups of order n.

A055562.name: a(n) = least number greater than a(n-1) not the sum of an earlier pair of consecutive terms, a(0) = 2.
formula: a(2n) = 3n+1 + (floor(log_2 n) mod 2), n >= 1; a(2n+1) = 3n+3, n >= 0 - _Jeffrey Shallit_, Jun 08, 2000.

A055563.name: a(n) = least number greater than a(n-1) not the sum of an earlier pair of consecutive terms, a(0) = 3.

A055568.name: Numbers n such that sum of digits of n^2 is >= n.

A055569.name: Sum of digits of a(n)^3 is greater than or equal to a(n).

A055570.name: Sum of digits of (a(n)^4) is greater than or equal to a(n).

A055571.name: Sum of digits of a(n)^5 is greater than or equal to a(n).

A055572.name: Sum of digits of a(n)^6 is greater than or equal to a(n).

A055573.name: Number of terms in simple continued fraction for n-th harmonic number H_n = Sum_{k=1..n} (1/k).
formula: It appears that lim n -> infinity a(n)/n = C = 0.84... - _Benoit Cloitre_, May 04 2002
Conjecture: limit n -> infinity a(n)/n = 12*log(2)/Pi^2 = 0.84..... = A089729 Levy's constant. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Jan 17 2004

A055575.name: Sum of digits of n^4 is equal to n.

A055576.name: Sum of digits of a(n)^5 is equal to a(n).

A055577.name: Sum of digits of a(n)^6 is equal to a(n).

A055578.name: "Non-generous primes": primes p whose least positive primitive root is not a primitive root of p^2.
formula: Prime A000040(n) is in this sequence iff A001918(n)^(A000040(n)-1) == 1 (mod A000040(n)^2).
Prime A000040(n) is in this sequence iff A001918(n) differs from A127807(n).

A055580.name: Björner-Welker sequence: 2^n*(n^2 + n + 2) - 1.
formula: Partial sums of A001788 (without leading zero). - _Paul Barry_, Jun 26 2003
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n+1} Sum_{i=0..n+1} i^2 * C(k,i). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Sep 21 2017

A055584.name: Triangle of partial row sums (prs) of triangle A055252.
formula: a(n, m)=sum(A055252(n, k), k=m..n), n >= m >= 0, a(n, m) := 0 if n<m, (sequence of partial row sums in column m).
Column m recursion: a(n, m)= sum(a(j, m), j=m..n-1)+ A055252(n, m), n >= m >= 0, a(n, m) := 0 if n<m.

A055585.name: Second column of triangle A055584.
formula: Preceded by 0, this is the binomial transform of the tetrahedral numbers A000292. - _Carl Najafi_, Sep 08 2011

A055587.name: Triangle with columns built from row sums of the partial row sums triangles obtained from Pascal's triangle A007318. Essentially A049600 formatted differently.
formula: a(n, m)= Am(n, 0) if n >= m >= 0 and a(n, m) := 0 if n<m; i.e. first column of the lower triangular matrix Am := prs^(m)(A007318) with the lower triangular matrix A007318 (Pascal triangle) and prs^(m) is the partial row sums (prs) mapping for triangular matrices applied m times. See e.g. A055584 for m=4.
T(n, k) = sum_{j=0..n-k} C(n-k, j)*C(k+j-1, k-1). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Jan 14 2004

A055592.name: Longest side of congruent triangles with integer sides and positive integer area, ordered by longest side, then second longest side and finally shortest side.

A055593.name: Second longest side of congruent triangles with integer sides and positive integer area, ordered by longest side, then second longest side and finally shortest side.

A055594.name: Shortest side of congruent triangles with integer sides and positive integer area, ordered by longest side, then second longest side and finally shortest side.

A055595.name: Area of congruent triangles with integer sides and positive integer area, ordered by longest side, then second longest side and finally shortest side.
formula: a(n) = sqrt(s(n)*(s(n)-A055592(n))*(s(n)-A055593(n))*(s(n)-A055594(n))) where s(n) = (A055592(n)+A055593(n)+A055594(n))/2 i.e. half the perimeter of the triangle

A055596.name: E.g.f. (2-x-2/exp(x))/(1-x).
formula: For n>2, a(n) = floor(n! * (1-2*exp(-1)) + 1/2). - _Peter Bala_, Oct 08 2013

A055598.name: Even numbers not the sum of two terms from A034757.

A055599.name: Triangle T(n,k)r read by rows, giving the number of n X n binary matrices with no zero rows or columns and with k=0..n^2 ones.
formula: Number of m X n binary matrices with no zero rows or columns and with k=0..m*n ones is Sum_{i=0..n} (-1)^i*C(n, i)*a(m, n-i, k) where a(m, n, k)=Sum_{i=0..m} (-1)^i*C(m, i)*C((m-i)*n, k).
G.f. for n-th row: Sum_{k=0..n} (-1)^(n-k)*binomial(n, k)*((1+x)^k-1)^n. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Apr 04 2003

A055600.name: Numbers of form 2^i*3^j+1 with i, j >= 0.

A055601.name: Number of n X n binary matrices with no zero rows.
formula: E.g.f.: A(x) = Sum_{n>=0} 2^(n^2) * exp(-2^n*x) * x^n/n!. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Jan 02 2008

A055602.name: Number of n X n binary matrices with no 0 rows or columns and with n+1 1's.
formula: Number of m X n binary matrices with no zero rows or columns and with k=0..m*n ones is Sum_{i=0..n} (-1)^i*binomial(n, i)*a(m, n-i, k) where a(m, n, k)=Sum_{i=0..m} (-1)^i*binomial(m, i)*binomial((m-i)*n, k).

A055603.name: Number of n X n binary matrices with no zero rows or columns and with n+2 ones.
formula: Number of m X n binary matrices with no zero rows or columns and with k=0..m*n ones is Sum_{i=0..n} (-1)^i*C(n, i)*a(m, n-i, k) where a(m, n, k)=Sum_{i=0..m} (-1)^i*C(m, i)*C((m-i)*n, k).

A055604.name: Primes such that (a) reversal of digits gives a prime, (b) deleting any digit gives a prime and (c) reversing digits and deleting any digit gives a prime.

A055605.name: Number of balanced basic magic carpets on n points.

A055606.name: Largest k value that admits an (n,k) balanced magic carpet.

A055609.name: Number of 3 X n binary matrices with no zero rows or columns, up to row and column permutation.

A055611.name: n written efficiently in natural numbers base, i.e., in form ...wxyz where n = 1*z + 2*y + 3*x + 4*w + ... with z <= 1, y < 2, x < 3, w < 4, ...

A055614.name: Number of isomorphism classes of complex filiform Lie algebras of dimension n.

A055615.name: a(n) = n*moebius(n) (cf. A008683).
formula: Multiplicative with a(p^e) = -p*0^(e-1), e>0 and p prime. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jul 17 2003

Conjectures: lim b->1+ Sum n=1..inf a(n)*b^(-n) = -12 and lim b->1- Sum n=1..inf a(n)*b^n = -12 (+ indicates that b decreases to 1, - indicates it increases to 1), both considering that zeta(-1) = -1/12 and calculations (more generally mu(n)*n^s is Abel summable to zeta(-s)). - _Gerald McGarvey_, Sep 26 2004
Dirichlet generating function for the absolute value: zeta(s-1)/zeta(2s-2). - _Franklin T. Adams-Watters_, Sep 11 2005
G.f. A(x) satisfies: A(x) = x - Sum_{k>=2} k*A(x^k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, May 11 2019

A055616.name: Numbers, with an even number of digits, that are the sum of the squares of their two halves (leading zeros allowed only for the second half).

A055621.name: Number of covers of an unlabeled n-set.
formula: Euler transform of A323819. - _Gus Wiseman_, Aug 14 2019

A055622.name: Minimum solution for tri-color tower of Hanoi, restricted so like colors can't be together.

A055623.name: First occurrence of run of primes congruent to 1 mod 4 of exactly length n.
formula: Compute sequence of primes congruent to 1 mod 4. When first occurrence of run of exactly length n is found, add first prime to sequence.

A055624.name: First occurrence of run of primes congruent to 3 mod 4 of exactly length n.
formula: Compute sequence of primes congruent to 3 mod 4. When first occurrence of run of exactly length n is found, add first prime to sequence.

A055625.name: First prime starting a chain of exactly n consecutive primes congruent to 1 modulo 6.

A055626.name: First prime starting a chain of exactly n consecutive primes congruent to 5 modulo 6.

A055627.name: From Vikram Seth's novel, "A Suitable Boy".

A055628.name: Primes p for which the period of the reciprocal 1/p is (p-1)/3.

A055629.name: Beginning of first run of at least n consecutive happy numbers.

A055630.name: Table T(k,m) = k^2 + m read by antidiagonals.

A055631.name: Sum of Euler's totient function phi of distinct primes dividing n.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{p divides n} p-1 = A008472(n) - A001221(n).
If n = p^w, a power of prime, then a(n) = p-1; if n = 2p, then a(n) = p = n/2.

A055632.name: Sum of totient function of primes dividing n is a prime.

A055633.name: Number of nested algorithms a(m,n) where m is the number of items in a contaminated group and n is the total number of unclassified items (0 <= m <= n) (values read by antidiagonals).
formula: a(0, 0)=1, a(0, 1)=1, a(0, n) = C(n+1)*product(a(0, i), i=1..n-1) for n >= 2 and a(m, n) = C(m)*product(a(0, n-i), i=1..m) for 1 <= m <= n. Here C(n) equals the Catalan number given by binomial(2n-2, n-1)/n.

A055634.name: 2-adic factorial function.
formula: a(n) = (-1)^n*n!/A037223(n), A037223(n) = 2^floor(n/2)*floor(n/2)!. Exponential generating function: (1-x)*exp(x^2/2). - Antonio G. Astudillo (afg_astudillo(AT)hotmail.com), Nov 01 2002

A055635.name: Smallest number that can be expressed as the sum of distinct Lucas numbers (A000204) in exactly n ways.

A055637.name: (n-1)!/n or 0 if n does not divide (n-1)!..

A055638.name: Numbers n for which sigma(n^2) is prime.
formula: Equal to A000961 \ A248963. - _M. F. Hasler_, Oct 19 2014

A055639.name: Number of nonzero digits of n which are not factors of n.

A055640.name: Number of nonzero digits in decimal expansion of n.
formula: a(n) = sum_{j=1..m+1} (floor(n/10^j+0.9) - floor(n/10^j)), where m = floor(log_10(n)).

A055641.name: Number of zero digits in n.
formula: a(n) = m + 1 - A055640(n) = Sum_{j=1..m+1} (1 + floor(n/10^j) - floor(n/10^j+0.9)), where m = floor(log_10(n)).
a(n) = if n<10 then A000007(n) else a(A059995(n)) + A000007(A010879(n)). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Apr 30 2013, corrected by _M. F. Hasler_, Jun 22 2018

A055642.name: Number of digits in decimal expansion of n.
formula: a(n) = 1 + floor(log_10(n)) = 1 + A004216(n) = ceiling(log_10(n+1)) = A004218(n+1), if n >= 1. - _Daniel Forgues_, Mar 27 2014
a(n) = A117804((n+1) - A117804(n), n>0. - _Hieronymus Fischer_, Jun 08 2012

A055643.name: Babylonian numbers: integers in base 60 with each sexagesimal digit represented by 2 decimal digits, leading zeros omitted.

A055644.name: Integers in base 20 with each base 20 digit represented by 2 decimal digits.

A055645.name: Integers in base 16 with each hexadecimal digit represented by 2 decimal digits.

A055646.name: Integers in base 15 with each base 15 digit represented by 2 decimal digits.

A055647.name: Integers in base 14 with each base 14 digit represented by 2 decimal digits.

A055648.name: Integers in base 13 with each base 13 digit represented by 2 decimal digits.

A055649.name: Integers in base 11 with each base 11 digit represented by 2 decimal digits.

A055650.name: Numbers k such that k | phi(k)*d(k) - sigma(k), where phi=A000010, d=A000005 and sigma=A000203.

A055651.name: Table read by rows: T(m,k)=m^k-k^m (with 0^0 assumed to be finite).

A055652.name: Table T(m,k)=m^k+k^m (with 0^0 taken to be 1) as square array read by antidiagonals.
formula: E.g.f. Sum(n,m, T(n,m)/(n! m!)) = e^(x e^y) + e^(y e^x). [From _Franklin T. Adams-Watters_, Oct 26 2009]

A055653.name: Sum of phi(d) [A000010] over all unitary divisors d of n (that is, gcd(d,n/d) = 1).
formula: If n = product p_i^e_i, a(n) = product (1+p_i^e_i-p_i^(e_i-1)). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Apr 19 2001
Dirichlet g.f.: zeta(s)*zeta(s-1)*product_{primes p} (1+p^(-2s)-p^(1-2s)-p^(-s)). - _R. J. Mathar_, Oct 24 2011
Dirichlet convolution square of A318661(n)/A318662(n). - _Antti Karttunen_, Sep 03 2018
Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ c * Pi^2 * n^2 / 12, where c = Product_{primes p} (1 - 1/p^2 - 1/p^3 + 1/p^4) = A330523 = 0.535896... - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Dec 17 2019

A055654.name: Difference between n and the result of "Phi-summation" over unitary divisors of n.
formula: a(n) = n - Sum_{u|n, gcd(u,n/u) = 1} phi(u), i.e. when u is a unitary divisor of n.

A055655.name: Efficient representation of n in "square base" where xyz means 9x+4y+z and z<4, y<9 and x<16 etc.

A055656.name: Excess in exponents of powers of 2 in EulerPhi of n! compared to that of n!.

A055657.name: If a(n) is prime, a(n+1) = a(n) followed by a 1; if a(n) is composite, a(n+1) = concatenation of distinct prime factors of a(n).

A055658.name: Number of (3,n)-partitions of a chain of length n^2.

A055659.name: Number of (2,n)-partitions of a chain of length n^3.

A055660.name: Number of (2,2; n,n)-partitions of a chain of length n^2 + n.

A055661.name: Tower of Hanoi positions (A055662) converted from base 3 to base 10.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{j=0..floor(log_2(n))} 3^j*((-1)^j*floor((n/2^j + 1)/2) mod 3). - Corrected by _Stefano Spezia_, Oct 27 2018

A055662.name: Successive positions in Tower of Hanoi (with three pegs {0,1,2}) where xyz means smallest disk is on peg z, second smallest is on peg y, third smallest on peg x, etc. and leading zeros indicate largest disks are all on peg 0.

A055663.name: Number of (3,3; n,n)-partitions of a chain of length n^2 + n.
formula: D-finite with recurrence: (-9*n+n^2)*a(n) - (42-26*n+4*n^2)*a(n-1) = 0, a(9) = 220 for n >= 10. - _Georg Fischer_, May 29 2021

A055664.name: Norms of Eisenstein-Jacobi primes.
formula: Consists of 3; rational primes = 1 (mod 3) [A002476]; and squares of rational primes = -1 (mod 3) [A003627^2].

A055665.name: Number of Eisenstein-Jacobi primes of successive norms (indexed by A055664).

A055666.name: Number of inequivalent Eisenstein-Jacobi primes of successive norms (indexed by A055664).

A055667.name: Number of Eisenstein-Jacobi primes of norm n.

A055668.name: Number of inequivalent Eisenstein-Jacobi primes of norm n.
formula: a(n) = 2 if n is a prime = 1 (mod 6); a(n) = 1 if n = 3 or n = p^2 where p is a prime = 2 (mod 3); a(n) = 0 otherwise. - _Franklin T. Adams-Watters_, May 05 2006

A055669.name: Number of prime Hurwitz quaternions of norm prime(n).

A055671.name: Number of prime Hurwitz quaternions of norm n.
formula: a(n) = number of vectors of norm n in D_4 lattice (A004011) if n is a prime, otherwise a(n) = 0.

A055672.name: Number of right-inequivalent prime Hurwitz quaternions of norm n.

A055673.name: Absolute values of norms of primes in ring of integers Z[sqrt(2)].
formula: Consists of 2; rational primes = +-1 (mod 8); and squares of rational primes = +-3 (mod 8).

A055674.name: a(n) = least nonnegative integer h such that (n,h) is not collinear with any 2 points in the set S(n-1) := {(m,a(m)), (m,b(m)): m = 0,1,...,n-1} for n >= 1.

A055675.name: b(n) = least nonnegative integer h such that (n,h) is not collinear with any 2 points in the set S(n-1)union{(n,a(n))}, set S(n-1) and sequence a(n) as in A055674.

A055676.name: b(n)-a(n), where a, b are given by A055674, A055675.

A055677.name: Smallest k>n where n is a 6th power modulo k.

A055678.name: Integers not congruent to 0 (mod 6) that are divisible by the number of their divisors.

A055679.name: Number of distinct prime factors of phi(n!).

A055681.name: Numbers n such that n | sigma(n)-phi(n).

A055682.name: a(n) = floor(n*sqrt(n)) - sigma(n), where sigma(n) is the sum of the divisors of n (A000203).

A055683.name: Number of Gaussian primes (in the first half quadrant; i.e., 0 to 45 degrees) with real part <= 10^n.

A055696.name: Numbers n such that n | Sigma_2(n) + Phi(n)^2.

A055697.name: Numbers k such that k | sigma_3(k) - phi(k)^3.

A055698.name: Numbers n such that n | (sigma_4(n) + phi(n)^4).

A055699.name: Numbers n such that n | (sigma_5(n) - phi(n)^5).

A055700.name: Numbers n such that n | Sigma_6(n) + Phi(n)^6.

A055701.name: Numbers n such that n | Sigma_7(n) - Phi(n)^7.

A055702.name: Numbers n such that n | Sigma_8(n) + Phi(n)^8.

A055703.name: Numbers n such that n | sigma_9(n) - phi(n)^9.

A055704.name: Numbers n such that n | sigma_10(n) + phi(n)^10.

A055705.name: Numbers n such that n | Sigma_11(n) - Phi(n)^11.

A055706.name: Numbers n such that n | sigma_12(n) + phi(n)^12.

A055707.name: Numbers k such that k | sigma_13(k) - phi(k)^13.

A055708.name: Numbers n such that n - 1 | sigma(n).

A055709.name: Numbers k such that k | sigma_5(k).

A055710.name: Numbers k such that k | sigma_6(k).

A055711.name: Numbers k such that k | sigma_7(k).

A055712.name: Numbers k such that k | sigma_8(k).

A055713.name: Numbers k such that k | sigma_9(k).

A055714.name: Numbers n such that n | sigma_10(n).

A055715.name: Numbers k such that k | sigma_11(k).

A055716.name: Numbers n such that n | sigma_12(n).

A055717.name: Numbers n such that n | sigma_13(n).

A055719.name: d(n)-1 | n and n is not prime.

A055720.name: Numbers k such that d(k)+1 | k.

A055721.name: Numbers n such that sigma_2(n)/n > sigma_2(k)/k for all k < n.

A055722.name: Sigma_3(n)/n > Sigma_3(k)/k for all k < n.

A055733.name: Sum of third powers of coefficients in full expansion of (z1+z2+...+zn)^n.
formula: a(n) is coefficient of x^n in expansion of n!^3*(1+x/1!^3+x^2/2!^3+x^3/3!^3+...+x^n/n!^3)^n.

A055734.name: Number of distinct primes dividing phi(n).

A055735.name: The x value of the unique nontrivial solution to x^3 + d*y^3 = 1 for all admissible (d = 2,7,9,17,..., A005988).

A055736.name: Difference between number of prime factors of n and of phi(n).

A055737.name: Number of prime triples < 10^n, where a prime triple means 3 successive primes of the form {p, p+2, p+4} or {p, p+4, p+6}.

A055738.name: Number of prime quadruples < 10^n, where a prime quadruple means 4 successive primes {p, p', p'', p'''} with p''' = p + 8.

A055740.name: Sum of fourth powers of coefficients in full expansion of (z1+z2+...+zn)^n.
formula: a(n) is coefficient of x^n in expansion of n!^4*(1+x/1!^4+x^2/2!^4+x^3/3!^4+...+x^n/n!^4)^n.

A055741.name: Phi(n) has more distinct prime factors than n.

A055742.name: Numbers k such that k and EulerPhi(k) have same number of prime factors, counted without multiplicity.

A055743.name: Phi(n) has fewer distinct prime divisors than n.

A055744.name: Numbers k such that k and phi(k) have same prime factors.

A055745.name: Squarefree numbers not of form ab + bc + ca for 1 <= a <= b <= c (probably the list is complete).

A055746.name: Product of first n terms of A003046.
formula: a(n) = Product_{k=1..n} (2^((k+1)/2) * sqrt(BarnesG(2*k)) * Gamma(2*k) / (BarnesG(k) * BarnesG(k+3) * Gamma(k)^(3/2))). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Mar 02 2019

A055747.name: Expansion of Jacobi form of weight 12 and index 1 for the Niemeier lattice of type E_8^3 or D_16+E_8.

A055748.name: A chaotic cousin of the Hofstadter-Conway sequence A004001.
formula: a(1) = 1, a(2) = 1, a(n) = a(a(n-1)) + a(n - a(n-2) - 1) for n >= 3. [_Jaroslav Krizek_, Dec 09 2009]

A055749.name: Jacobi form of weight 12 and index 1 for the Niemeier lattice of type D_24.
formula: E_8*E_{4, 1}+32*phi_12. phi_12=unique Jacobi cusp form of weight 12 index 1.

A055750.name: Jacobi form of weight 12 and index 1 for the Niemeier lattice of type D_12^2.

A055751.name: Jacobi form of weight 12 and index 1 for Niemeier lattice of type A_24.

A055752.name: Jacobi form of weight 12 and index 1 for Niemeier lattice of type A_17*E_7 or D_10*E_7^2.

A055753.name: Jacobi form of weight 12 and index 1 for Niemeier lattice of type A_15 D_9.

A055754.name: Jacobi form of weight 12 and index 1 for Niemeier lattice of type D_8^3.

A055756.name: Jacobi form of weight 12 and index 1 for Niemeier lattice of type A_12^2.

A055757.name: Jacobi form of weight 12 and index 1 for Niemeier lattice of type E_6^4 or A_11 D_7 E_6.

A055758.name: Jacobi form of weight 12 and index 1 for Niemeier lattice of type D_6^4 or A_9^2 D_6.

A055759.name: Jacobi form of weight 12 and index 1 for Niemeier lattice of type A_8^3.

A055760.name: Jacobi form of weight 12 and index 1 for Niemeier lattice of type A_7^2 D_5^2.

A055761.name: Jacobi form of weight 12 and index 1 for Niemeier lattice of type A_6^4.

A055762.name: Jacobi form of weight 12 and index 1 for Niemeier lattice of type A_5^4 D_4 or D_4^6.

A055763.name: Jacobi form of weight 12 and index 1 for Niemeier lattice of type A_4^6.

A055764.name: Jacobi form of weight 12 and index 1 for Niemeier lattice of type A_3^8.

A055765.name: Jacobi form of weight 12 and index 1 for Niemeier lattice of type A_2^12.

A055766.name: Jacobi form of weight 12 and index 1 for Niemeier lattice of type A_1^24.

A055767.name: Index (or subscript) of the largest primorial (A002110(k)) which divides EulerPhi of the n-th primorial ((A005867(n)).

A055768.name: Number of distinct primes dividing phi of n-th primorial number.
formula: a(n) < n. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Sep 02 2015

A055769.name: Largest prime dividing phi of the n-th primorial.

A055770.name: Largest factorial number which divides n.

A055771.name: Multiplicity of irreducible character IRR2 of Monster simple group in n-th head character.

A055772.name: Square root of largest square dividing n!.

A055773.name: a(n) = product(p in P_n) where P_n = {p prime, n/2 < p <= n }.
formula: a(n) = product of primes p such that n/2 < p <= n. - _Klaus Brockhaus_, May 02 2004
a(n) = Prod_{i=pi(n/2)+1..pi(n)} p(i), where pi denotes the prime counting function and p(i) denotes the i-th prime number. - _John M. Campbell_, Mar 27 2016

A055774.name: Least common multiple of n! and n^n.

A055776.name: a(n) = a(n-1)^3 + a(n-1)^2 + a(n-1) + 1.
formula: a(2n) mod 2 = 0 ; a(2n+1) mod 2 = 1. - _Altug Alkan_, Oct 04 2015

A055778.name: Number of 1's in base phi representation of n.
formula: a(n) = delta(x), where x is the fixed point starting with (0,0) of the morphism (j,0)->(j,0)(j,1), (j,1)->(j,2)(j,3), (j,2)->(j+2,0)(j+2,1)(j+2,2), (j,3)->(j+1,3)(j+2,2)(j+1,3) for all natural numbers j, and delta is the decoration morphism (j,0)-> j,j+1, (j,1)-> j+2, (j,2)-> j+2,j+3), (j,3)-> (j,3)(j,3) for all natural numbers j. - _Michel Dekking_, Feb 06 2021

A055779.name: Number of fat trees on n labeled vertices.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} binomial(n, k)*k^(n-k)*n^(k-2). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Jun 16 2006
a(n) = n!/n^2 sum_{mu a partition of n} product_j n^{mu_j}/(mu_j! (j-1)!^{mu_j}), where mu_j is the number of parts of size j in the partition mu. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Jun 15 2006

limit n->infinity (a(n)^(1/n))/n = (1-p)^(p-1)*p^(1-2*p) ~ 1.6554879129915343..., where p ~ 0.6924583254616546... is the root of the equation exp(1-1/p)=(1-p)/p^2. [From _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Aug 25 2012]

A055780.name: Number of symmetric types of (3,2n)-hypergraphs under action of complementing group C(3,2).

A055781.name: Primes q of the form q = 10p + 1, where p is also prime.

A055782.name: Primes q of the form q = 10p + 3, where p is also prime.

A055783.name: Primes q of form q=10p+7, where p is also prime.

A055784.name: Primes q of form q = 10p + 9, where p is also prime.

A055785.name: a(n) = smallest prime q of form q=-1+(p+1)*10^w, where p is n-th prime.

A055786.name: Numerators of Taylor series expansion of arcsin(x). Also arises from arccos(x), arccsc(x), arcsec(x), arcsinh(x).

A055787.name: a(n) = 2^(4*n-1) - 2^(2*n-1)*binomial(2*n,n).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n-1} binomial(4*k+2, 2*k+1) * binomial(4*n-4*k-2, 2*n-2*k-1). (LHS of Gould's identity, corrected).
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n-1}(2^(2*n) * C(2*n, k)). - _David Scambler_, Aug 13 2012

A055788.name: Number of symmetric types of (5,2n)-hypergraphs under action of complementing group C(5,2).

A055790.name: a(n) = n*a(n-1) + (n-2)*a(n-2), a(0) = 0, a(1) = 2.
formula: G.f.: Q(0)*(1+x)/x - 1/x - 2, where Q(k)= 1 + (2*k + 1)*x/( (1+x) - 2*x*(1+x)*(k+1)/(2*x*(k+1) + (1+x)/Q(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 08 2013
G.f.: (1+x)^2/x/Q(0) - 1/x - 2, where Q(k)= 1 - 2*k*x - x^2*(k + 1)^2/Q(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 08 2013
G.f.: 2*(1+x)/G(0) - 1-x, where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x*(2*k+2)/(x*(2*k+1) - 1 + x*(2*k+2)/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 31 2013
G.f.: W(0) -1, where W(k) = 1 - x*(k+2)/( x*(k+1) - 1/(1 - x*(k+1)/( x*(k+1) - 1/W(k+1) ))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Aug 26 2013

A055791.name: Table giving multiplicity of k-th irreducible character of Monster simple group in n-th head character, read by antidiagonals.

A055792.name: a(n) and floor(a(n)/2) are both squares; i.e., squares which remain squares when written in base 2 and last digit is removed.
formula: a(n) = c*k^n + 1/2 + o(1) with k = 17+sqrt(288) = 33.97... and c = 17/4 - sqrt(18). - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, May 07 2015

A055793.name: Numbers n such that n and floor[n/3] are both squares; i.e., squares which remain squares when written in base 3 and last digit is removed.
formula: a(n) = 14*a(n-1)-a(n-2)-6, with a(0)=1, a(1)=4. (See Brown and Shiue)
a(n) = (A001075(n-2))^2. - _Johannes Boot_ Dec 16 2011, corrected by _M. F. Hasler_, Jan 15 2012

A055794.name: Triangle T read by rows: T(i,0)=1 for i >= 0; T(i,i)=0 for i=0,1,2,3; T(i,i)=0 for i >= 4; T(i,j) = T(i-1,j) + T(i-2,j-1) for 1<=j<=i-1.

A055795.name: a(n) = binomial(n,4) + binomial(n,2).
formula: a(n+1) = C(n, 1) + C(n, 2) + C(n, 3) + C(n, 4). - _James A. Sellers_, Mar 16 2002
Row sums of triangle A134394. Also, binomial transform of [1, 2, 2, 2, 1, 0, 0, 0,...]. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Oct 23 2007

A055796.name: T(2n+3,n), array T as in A055794.
formula: a(n-4) = binomial(n,6) + binomial(n,4) for n>3. - _Zerinvary Lajos_, Jul 24 2006

A055797.name: T(2n+4,n), array T as in A055794.
formula: a(n-5) = binomial(n,7) + binomial(n,5) for n>4. - _Zerinvary Lajos_, Jul 24 2006

A055798.name: T(2n+5,n), array T as in A055794.

A055799.name: T(2n+6,n), array T as in A055794.

A055800.name: Triangle T read by rows: T(i,0)=1 for i >= 0; T(i,i)=0 for i >= 1; T(i,j) = Sum_{k=1..floor(i/2)} T(i-2k,j-2k+1) for 1 <= j <= i-1, where T(m,n) := 0 if m < 0 or n < 0.
formula: G.f. for k-th diagonal: (1-x^2-x*(x/(1-x^2))^k)/(1-x-x^2). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Mar 10 2005

A055801.name: Triangle T read by rows: T(i,0)=T(i,i)=1, T(i,j) = Sum_{k=1..floor(n/2)} T(i-2k, j-2k+1) for 1<=j<=i-1, where T(m,n) := 0 if m<0 or n<0.

A055802.name: a(n) = T(n,n-2), array T as in A055801.

A055803.name: a(n) = T(n,n-3), array T as in A055801.

A055804.name: a(n) = T(n,n-4), array T as in A055801.

A055805.name: a(n) = T(n,n-5), array T as in A055801.

A055806.name: a(n) = T(n,n-6), array T as in A055801.

A055807.name: Triangle T read by rows: T(i,j) = R(i-j,j), where R(i,0) = 1 for i >= 0, R(0,j) = 0 for j >= 1, and R(i,j) = Sum_{h=0..i-1, k=0..j} R(h,k) for i >= 1 and j >= 1.
formula: T(n,k) = (n-k)*hypergeom([-n + k + 1, k], [2], -1) = Sum_{s=1..n-k} binomial(n-k,s)*binomial(s+k-2,k-1) for 1 <= k <= n.
T(n,k) = 2*T(n-1,k) + T(n-1,k-1) - T(n-2,k-1) for 2 <= k <= n-1 with initial conditions T(n,0) = 1 for n >= 0, T(n,n) = 0 for n >= 1, and T(n,1) = 2^(n-1) - 1 for n >= 2. (End)

A055808.name: a(n) and floor(a(n)/4) are both squares; i.e., squares that remain squares when written in base 4 and last digit is removed.

A055809.name: a(n) = T(n,n-4), array T as in A055807.

A055810.name: a(n) = T(n,n-5), array T as in A055807.

A055811.name: a(n) = T(n,n-6), array T as in A055807.

A055812.name: a(n) and floor(a(n)/5) are both squares; i.e., squares which remain squares when written in base 5 and last digit is removed.

A055815.name: a(n) = T(2*n+3,n), array T as in A055807.
formula: a(n) = (n+3)*hypergeom([-n-2, n], [2], -1) = Sum_{s=1..n+3} binomial(n+3,s) * binomial(s+n-2,n-1) for n >= 1. - _Petros Hadjicostas_, Feb 13 2021

A055816.name: a(n) = T(2*n+4,n), array T as in A055807.
formula: a(n) = (n+4)*hypergeom([-n -3, n], [2], -1) = Sum_{s=1..n+4} binomial(n+4,s)*binomial(s+n-2,n-1) for n >= 1. - _Petros Hadjicostas_, Feb 13 2021

A055817.name: a(n) = T(2n+5,n), array T as in A055807.
formula: a(n) = (n+5)*hypergeom([-n-4, n], [2], -1) = Sum_{s=1..n+5} binomial(n+5,s) * binomial(s+n-2,n-1) for n >= 1. - _Petros Hadjicostas_, Feb 13 2021

A055858.name: Coefficient triangle for certain polynomials.

A055861.name: Essentially A053506 but with leading 0 (instead of 1) and offset 0.

A055862.name: Fourth column of triangle A055858.
formula: E.g.f.: -x*(1+4*x)/2 + (W(-x)^2)*(1-W(-x))/((1+W(-x))*x*2), W(x) principal branch of Lambert's function.

A055863.name: Fifth column of triangle A055858.

A055864.name: Coefficient triangle for certain polynomials.

A055865.name: Second column of triangle A055864.
formula: E.g.f.: -1/2*(-W(-x)^2+x^2)/x, W(x) principal branch of Lambert's function.

A055866.name: Largest number that has the same number of digits in base 10 and base n, or 0 if no such number exists.

A055867.name: Fourth column of triangle A055864.

A055869.name: a(n) = (n+1)^n - n^n.

With interpolated zeros, ceiling(n/2)^floor(n/2) - floor(n/2)^floor(n/2). - _Paul Barry_, Jul 13 2005

a(n) ~ (5+sqrt(5) - (-1)^n*(5-sqrt(5))) * sqrt(2) * 5^(n/2) / (8 * sqrt(Pi) * n^(3/2)). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Feb 13 2014
a(n) = a(n-1) if n is even. a(n) = a(n-1)+A002212((n-1)/2) if n is odd. [Cyvin (1992) eq (14)] - _R. J. Mathar_, Dec 15 2020

G.f.: G(0)/2 where G(k) = 1 - (2*x*k + 1)/(2*x*k - 1 - 2*x*(2*x*k - 1)/(2*x + (2*x*k + 1)/G(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jan 30 2013
G.f.: 1/Q(0), where Q(k)= 1 - 2*(k+1)*x - 4*(k+1)*x^2/Q(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 03 2013
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(n,k) * A004211(k) * A004211(n-k). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Apr 17 2020

a(n) = IF(mod(n; 2)=0; (((1 - sqrt(2))^n + (1 + sqrt(2))^n)/2)^2; 2*((((1 - sqrt(2))^(n + 1) + (1 + sqrt(2))^(n + 1)) - (((1 - sqrt(2))^n + (1 + sqrt(2))^n)))/4)^2). The odd-indexed terms are a(2n + 1) = [A001333(2n)]^2; the even-indexed terms are a(2n) = [A001333(2n - 1)]^2 + 1 = 2*[A001653(n)]^2. - _Antonio Alberto Olivares_, Jan 31 2004; corrected by _Bernard Schott_, Apr 20 2020
a(n) = (1/2) + (1/4)*(3+2*sqrt(2))^(n-1) + (1/4)*(3-2*sqrt(2))^(n-1). - _Antonio Alberto Olivares_, Feb 21 2006; corrected by _Michel Marcus_, Apr 20 2020
a(n) = A001653(n)-A001652(n-1). - _Charlie Marion_, Apr 10 2006; corrected by _Michel Marcus_, Apr 20 2020

a(n) = 2*A001653(m)*A011900(n-m-1) +A002315(m)*A001652(n-m-1) - A001108(m) with m<n; otherwise, a(n) = 2*A001653(m)*A011900(m-n) - A002315(m)*A046090(m-n) - A001108(m). See Link to Generalized Proof re Square Triangular Numbers. - _Kenneth J Ramsey_, Oct 13 2011
a(n) = 1 + sum{k=0..n-2} A002315(k). - _David Pasino_, Jul 09 2016; corrected by _Michel Marcus_, Apr 20 2020
Lim_{n -> infinity} a(n)/a(n-1) = A156035. - _César Aguilera_, Apr 07 2018
a(n) = (1/4)*(t^2 + t^(-2) + 2), where t = (1+sqrt(2))^(n-1). - _Ridouane Oudra_, Nov 29 2019

A055998.name: a(n) = n*(n+5)/2.
formula: a(n) = A126890(n,2) for n > 1. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Dec 30 2006
If we define f(n,i,m) = Sum_{k=0..n-i} binomial(n,k)*Stirling1(n-k,i)*Product_{j=0..k-1} (-m-j), then a(n) = -f(n,n-1,3), for n >= 1. - _Milan Janjic_, Dec 20 2008
a(n) = a(n-1) + n + 2 with a(0)=0. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Aug 07 2010
a(n) = 3*n + A000217(n-1) = 3*n - floor(n/2) + floor(n^2/2). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jun 15 2013
a(n) = Sum_{i=3..n+2} i. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jun 28 2013
a(n) = A046691(n) + 1. Also, a(n) = A052905(n-1) + 2 = A055999(n-1) + 3 for n>0. - _Andrey Zabolotskiy_, May 18 2016

A055999.name: a(n) = n*(n + 7)/2.

a(n) = n + a(n-1) + 3 (with a(0)=0). - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Aug 07 2010
a(n) = 4n - floor(n/2) + floor(n^2/2). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jun 15 2013
a(n) = Sum_{i=4..n+3} i. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jun 28 2013

A056000.name: a(n) = n*(n+9)/2.
formula: a(n) = A126890(n,4) for n > 3. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Dec 30 2006
If we define f(n,i,a) = Sum_{k=0..(n-i)} binomial(n,k)*stirling1(n-k,i)*Product_{j=0..k-1} (-a-j), then a(n) = -f(n,n-1,5), for n >= 1. - _Milan Janjic_, Dec 20 2008
a(n) = 5n - floor(n/2) + floor(n^2/2). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jun 15 2013
